Which of the following propositions accurately describe the fundamental properties of electromagnetic (EM) waves?

Statement I: The electric and magnetic field vectors reach their maximum and minimum values simultaneously at any given point.
Statement II: The energy of the wave is distributed equally between the electric field and the magnetic field components.
Statement III: The electric field vector, the magnetic field vector, and the direction of propagation are all mutually perpendicular to each other.
Statement IV: Electromagnetic waves are self-propagating and do not require a physical medium to travel through.
questions.option_d: All of the above (I, II, III, and IV)

questions.question: For a hydrogen atom where an electron resides in its second excited state, the total energy ($E$) is measured at approximately $-1.51 \, \text{eV}$. Utilizing the virial theorem for a system governed by a $1/r$ potential, what is the specific kinetic energy ($K$) associated with the electron's orbital motion in this configuration?

A small bob tied to one end of a thin string of length $1 \, \text{m}$ is describing a vertical circle such that the ratio of the maximum tension to the minimum tension in the string is $5 : 1$. What is the velocity of the bob at its highest position in $\text{m/s}$? (Take $g = 10 \, \text{m/s}^2$)

A cubic box made of a metal sheet has a side length of $10 \, \text{units}$ at room temperature. The coefficient of linear expansion of the metal is $\alpha = 2 \times 10^{-4} / ^{\circ}\text{C}$. If the box is heated uniformly by a temperature increment of $\Delta T = 10 \, ^{\circ}\text{C}$, calculate the increase in the volume of the box ($\Delta V$) to the nearest integer.

A uniform magnetic field is defined by the vector $\vec{B}= (5 \hat{i}+10 \hat{j})\, \text{T}$. An electron enters this field with a velocity $\vec{u}=3 \hat{i}+5 \hat{j}\, \text{m/s}$. Determine the coefficient $\alpha$ if the resulting magnetic force acting on the electron is expressed as $\vec{F}=\alpha e \hat{k}\, \text{N}$ (where $e$ is the elementary charge).

There exist a uniform magnetic field $B = 0.8\, \text{T}$ directed perpendicular to the plane of an elastic conducting circular loop. When released, the loop begins to shrink. At the instant the radius of the loop is $10\, \text{cm}$, the induced EMF in the loop is measured to be $50\, \text{mV}$. Calculate the rate of decrease in the radius of the loop at this instant.

A monochromatic beam of light is measured to have a wavelength of $30\, \text{\AA}$ ($30 \times 10^{-10}\, \text{m}$) while traveling through a medium with a refractive index of $n = 2$. What is the frequency of this radiation in PetaHertz (PHz)?

$$Cl_{2}(aq) + H_{2}S(aq) \rightarrow S(s) + 2H^{+}(aq) + 2Cl^{-}(aq)$$
The experimental rate equation is $\text{rate} = k[Cl_{2}][H_{2}S]$. Evaluate the following proposed mechanisms and identify which one is $\textbf{NOT}$ consistent with the observed rate law.

Which of the following statements correctly describes the behavior of a carbonyl compound possessing at least one hydrogen atom on its $\alpha$-carbon?
questions.option_a: The compound rapidly equilibrates with its corresponding enol form in a process known as carbonylation.
questions.option_b: The compound rapidly equilibrates with its corresponding enol form in a process known as keto-enol tautomerism.

Find the maximum element present in the set $\mathcal{W}$.
